==Description==
Niraloka Black, formerly known as Matte Black, was a unique type of black paint. It absorbed 100% of all light with no margin of error, creating a pure black surface. It is currently 'extinct', but was found in [[Level 9]], [[Level 6]], and [[Level 0.23]], alongside a [[Phenomenon 99|temporary manifestation]] as its home level. This temporary space was generated by [[Object 7|The Cross]], simultaneously creating the object.

<tabber>
|-| Veil Ink=

{{Blurimage|left|file=Black-Screen.png|hovertext=What were you expecting?|caption=An image of Veil Ink in [[Phenomenon 99|Level 9.9]].}}

Veil Ink, also known as God Blood, was the primary core of Niraloka Black. Veil Ink consists of three main chemicals: Sodium Hydroxide (15.24% abundance), Bromine (21.53% abundance), and [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] (63.23%). This makes Veil Ink an extremely corrosive substance. This chemical has only been separated from Niraloka Black, as it has not been found elsewhere. Whilst it has been hypothesized that Veil Ink can become a solid, there was no definitive proof.

|-| Negative Charge Converter=

The Negative Charge Converter was an intangible barrier, separating the Negative Particle Ring and the main core of Veil Ink. When passing through the Negative Particle Ring, the light's positive charge was influenced and converted to a negative one. The Negative Charge Converter converts this negative charge back to a positive charge, causing that light to be suspended between the Negative Particle Ring and the Veil Ink, as both carry a negative charge. The Negative Particle Ring has a much stronger charge. As a result, the light was slowly pushed to the Veil Ink, where, through unknown means, the photon particle was destroyed. No light escapes once it has touched the paint. It was comprised of Sha-Particles.

|-| Negative Particle Ring=

The Negative Particle Ring was a ring composed of Zhe-Particles, the sole purpose of which was to use its negative charge to repel light within its barriers. It was intangible and anomalously had no charge on its exterior, allowing light to pass through freely. However, when light passes through and reaches the Negative Charge Converter, the Negative Particle Ring becomes negatively charged on the interior. These particles that make up the ring are hypothesized to be variations of Noble Gases, as they have no radioactivity.
</tabber>
== Uses ==

{{Blurimage ALT|file=Niraloka West End.png|width=518px|caption= A suitcase painted with Niraloka Black in a bus stop in [[Level 91]].|hovertext=Look at me with a straight face and tell me that doesn't look like a black outline of a suitcase was added onto an image of the West End in Photoshop.}}

* Due to its pitch black color, painting oneself black would have proven useful to hide from hostile entities or wanderers in darker levels, such as [[Level 6]] or the very lowest floors of the [[Absolute Infinity of Unknown]]. It can also be used to conceal items in small nooks or naturally dark crannies. Given its nonreflective behavior, using it in levels with forms of lighting is not encouraged.

* The substance was highly toxic when ingested. Due to unknown circumstances, the Negative Charge Converter and the Negative Particle Ring both completely dissolve upon consumption, leaving only the Veil Ink. Veil Ink contains many hazardous chemicals as well as a high concentration of Liquid Pain. This means that weapons that force ingestion, like tranquilizer darts, can be filled with Niraloka Black and used as dangerous weapons.

== Variants ==
{{Blurimage|file=Niraloka Black Diagramme.png|caption=A simple diagram of Niraloka Black.|hovertext=The shapes are actually an approximation of the color of Niraloka Black!}}
The sole variant of Object 200 was referred to as Stygian Blue. Eyewitness accounts describe it as simultaneously deep blue and black. Its chemical composition was unknown. Exposure to the color causes Stygian Blue Disorder.

=== Stygian Blue Disorder ===

Stygian Blue Disorder was an ailment contracted upon viewing the color Stygian Blue. The person who contracts this ailment is referred to as 'Viewer' from now on. It requires roughly 5 seconds of uninterrupted eye contact to contract.

==== Stage I ====

Upon initial viewing, within two to five seconds, the viewer goes completely blind for a few seconds. Afterwards, they are unable to see any color, excluding Stygian Blue. Migraines are common at this stage. This was due to an overload of color in the light cones in the macula, which was known to cause minor brain damage.

==== Stage II ====

At this stage, occurring within one to three hours, the viewer will begin to describe in detail colors that should logically be impossible. The colors are as follows:

* Self-Luminous Red. Simultaneously brighter than white and identifiable as red.<ref>Self-Luminous Red was impossible because it should logically not be visible due to its being brighter than white.</ref>
* Hyperbolic Orange. A shade of orange with above 100% saturation.<ref>Hyperbolic Orange was also impossible, because a color cannot be above 100% saturation.</ref>
* Neon Brown. A shade of brown that was described as neon.<ref>Neon Brown was impossible, because neon requires brightness and saturation, while brown requires dimness and context, which are antitheses to brightness and saturation.</ref>
* Olo. A color described as blue-green, greener than any other shade of green, and of infinite saturation.<ref>Olo was theoretically impossible, as when one has an entirely green color, it cannot be seen as blue-green.</ref> A notable footnote was that this color has successfully been reproduced by using laser technology to isolate responses by M cones.
* Stygian Blue. A color that induces blindness, and Stygian Blue Disorder.

{{Blurimage|file=Stygian Blue Censored.png|width=518px|caption=An image of the sole variation, viewed in monochromatic black to prevent its cognitohazardous effects.|hovertext=God had no hand in making this color.}}

==== Stage III ====

The final stage occurs between 12 and 18 hours after viewing. The viewer becomes entirely blind and displays symptoms of Anton–Babinski syndrome. This blindness was irreversible, and the viewer will only be able to envision these impossible colors in their mind's eye. They will also be unable to visualize normal colors.

=== Cures ===

Stygian Blue Disorder could be completely cured in stages I to II by rewiring parts of the Hippocampus to remove the memory of the viewing. All symptoms will disappear. The most reliable method to do this was using [[Object 33|Memory Flame]]. Laser Eye Surgery may also be required to repair broken and damaged light cones. The blindness persists in stage three, but they will be unable to visualize the impossible colors and instead see the normal ones. As Stygian Blue was exclusively found in buckets inside houses painted in Niraloka Black within [[Level 9]], the number one way to prevent Stygian Blue Disorder was not to enter these houses.

== Discovery ==
Niraloka Black was discovered recently, at around 7:00 PM on November 5th, 2024. It was located in a formerly existent level, [[Phenomenon 99|Level 9.9]], by an unknown anonymous user. Afterward, M.E.G. reports verified the claim as true, followed by further encounters in [[Level 0.23]], [[Level 9]], and [[Level 6]]. In January of 2025, Stygian Blue was discovered.

In August of 2025, [[Phenomenon 99|Level 9.9]] began growing darker and darker, eventually becoming indistinguishable from [[The Void|the Void]], and around August 16th, completely merged with it. This has led to the broad consensus that [[Phenomenon 99|Level 9.9]] was merely a [[Phenomenon 99|Temporary Manifestation]]. At the same time, all samples of Niraloka Black, including its sole variant, abruptly disappeared.

Below is a message from an anonymous wanderer who encountered the object shortly after the discovery.
{{BacknetPost|author=Anonymous|message=Hey, I was in Level 9 and I found this weird black paint in a can, its like pitch black, anyone know what it was?[[File:Black-Screen.png|thumb|that's the thing]]|category=none}}

== Anomalous Properties ==
* Ingestion of Niraloka Black was not recommended due to the Veil Ink core. This core was normally protected; however, the Negative Particle Ring and Negative Charge Converter both dissolve upon contact with saliva. One would not only be ingesting Bromine and acid, but also [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]].

== Synthesis ==

Shortly before the object disappeared, studies were performed on the object, allowing insight into its methods of synthesis.

<span class="wds-button mw-customtoggle-scripts" style="border:#FFFFFF 5px; background: #000000; color: #FFFFFF">Method of Synthesis</span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-scripts">

# A [[Entity 69|Lightlurker]] dies, falling into a bed of moss and saturating it with its blood.

# Its blood reacts with the air in an unknown manner, creating Veil Ink.

# The Veil Ink mixed with the moss, combined with the Liquid Pain and Almond Water, with individual cells imploding due to the mixture, creating unique particles known as Zhe-Particles (symbol: ж) and Sha-Particles (symbol: ш). These particles are magnetized.

# The Sha-Particles and Zhe-Particles coalesce around the Veil Ink compound. The Sha-Particles hover closely around the Veil Ink, while the Zhe-Particles hover farther out. The Sha-Particles mix with the Veil Ink, entering their Majuscule-State (symbol: Ш). In their majuscule state, they become intangible on one surface while remaining tangible on the opposite, trapping light that enters.

# The Zhe-Particles through unknown means enter their Singularity-State (symbol: Ж), which has a high subatomic gravitational pull. It only affects high-speed weightless particles, and the only particles fitting this description are Photons.

# Once Photons interact with the Zhe-Particles, they enter their De-state (symbol: ДЖ), in which photons are pushed inwards, interacting with the Sha-Particles and inevitably disappearing upon contact with the Veil Ink core. Once the Photons have passed through, the Zhe-Particles return to their Singularity-State, waiting for the next photon.

# Through unknown means, the particles coalesce into paint buckets strewn across the levels it appears in. The working theory was that a large concentration of undetectable particles, labeled Yus-Particles (symbol: Ѫ), attracts the Sha- and Zhe-Particles, dragging the Veil Ink core along as well and entering the bucket. These buckets also appear rarely in [[Level 0.23]].
</div>

== Locations ==

*[[Level 9]], rarely painting roads and houses in the level, also found in cans.
*[[Level 0.23]], found scarcely in cans.
*[[Level 6]], where it paints certain surfaces within the level.


